{"id":"2103.03068","submitter":"Ignacio Garcia-Mata","authors":"A. M. Bilen, B. Georgeot, O. Giraud, G. Lemari\\'e and I. Garc\\'ia-Mata","title":"Symmetry Violation of Quantum Multifractality: Gaussian fluctuations\n  versus Algebraic Localization","comments":"Closest to published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 3, 022023 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.3.L022023","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum multifractality is a fundamental property of systems such as\nnon-interacting disordered systems at an Anderson transition and many-body\nsystems in Hilbert space. Here we discuss the origin of the presence or absence\nof a fundamental symmetry related to this property. The anomalous multifractal\ndimension $\\Delta_q$ is used to characterize the structure of quantum states in\nsuch systems. Although the multifractal symmetry relation\n\\mbox{$\\Delta_q=\\Delta_{1-q}$} is universally fulfilled in many known systems,\nrecently some important examples have emerged where it does not hold. We show\nthat this is the result of two different mechanisms. The first one was already\nknown and is related to Gaussian fluctuations well described by random matrix\ntheory. The second one, not previously explored, is related to the presence of\nan algebraically localized envelope. While the effect of Gaussian fluctuations\ncan be removed by coarse graining, the second mechanism is robust to such a\nprocedure. We illustrate the violation of the symmetry due to algebraic\nlocalization on two systems of very different nature, a 1D Floquet critical\nsystem and a model corresponding to Anderson localization on random graphs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Mar 2021 14:47:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 5 Mar 2021 15:58:38 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 11 Jun 2021 18:34:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-16"}
